Exactly! If your data is cheaply copyable (like slices), you can just allocate a new `Output` with its own owned data:

struct Input {
    data: Vec<u8>,
}

fn process(input: &Input) -> Output
{
    let output = Output { data: input.data.clone() };
    output
}

Then `output` has ownership of the data, so it won't be affected by lifetime issues. This is safer and idiomatic in Rust.

If your data isn’t copyable or you want to avoid cloning large amounts of data, then explicit lifetimes become even more important.

Yes! That's a very good practice. If you can avoid borrowing across function boundaries by instead transferring ownership or cloning data when needed, you sidestep lifetime problems entirely and make your code safer and easier to reason about.

If you still want to keep references but want multiple borrows with different lifetimes, then explicit lifetime annotations become essential — for example:

struct Input<'a> {
    data: &'a [u8],
}

struct Output<'a, 'b> {
    input_data: &'a [u8],
    output_data: &'b [u8],
}

Here you'd specify distinct lifetimes for different parts of the struct or function. But often in practice, transferring ownership is simpler and clearer.

