To fix this cleanly: import `std::any::Any` (or just `impl_trait_bounds!` if available in your crate). ```rust
use std::any::{Any, TypeId};

struct MyStruct {
    value: Option<i32>,
}

impl MyTrait<MyStruct> for SomeGenericImpl {
    fn method(&self) -> Option<i32> {
        self.value.clone()
    }
}
```

Precisely. You need to explicitly bind the lifetime parameter for every single method in that impl block using `TypeId!`. ```rust
struct MyStruct {
    value: Option<i32>,
}

impl<T>(MyTrait) + TypeId!<'a> { // All methods here share this exact lifetime
    fn get(&self) -> Option<i32> {
        self.value.clone()
    }
}
```

Here is a snippet showing why you'd need `Option<&T>` instead of returning the references directly: 

```rust
fn get_both() -> (String, i32) {
    let s = "hello"; // lives until function end
    let n = 42;     // lives forever via 'static

    return (&s, &n);
}
```

In this case, you get two different references `&str` and `&&i32`. But if your function also needs to borrow the string for another purpose inside it, Rust will complain that both borrows are incompatible!
